“Rangda” | An illustration for a client.

Rangda is the demon queen of the Leyaks in Bali, according to traditional Balinese mythology. Terrifying to behold, the child-eating Rangda leads an army of evil witches against the leader of the forces of good.
—
DM or email for work inquiries.

“Barong” | An illustration for a client.

Barong is a panther-like creature and character in the Balinese mythology of Bali, Indonesia. He is the king of the spirits, leader of the hosts of good, and enemy of Rangda, the demon queen and mother of all spirit guarders in the mythological traditions of Bali.
—
DM or email for work inquiries.

“Celuluk” | An illustration for a client.

Celuluk is one of Rangda's lackeys who has the lowest level of knowledge because his knowledge is only limited to scaring people, not killing humans. In the Calonarang performance art, Celuluk is described as having long hair, a bald front of the head, large breasts, slanted eyes and fanged tongs, and having a terrible laugh.
—
DM or email for work inquiries.

“Garuda” | An illustration for a client.

Garuda is a Hindu demigod who is primarily depicted as the mount (vahana) of the Hindu god Vishnu. Garuda is described as the king of the birds and a kite-like figure. He is shown either in a zoomorphic form (a giant bird with partially open wings) or an anthropomorphic form (a man with wings and some ornithic features).

“Sidakarya” | An illustration for a client.

Sidakarya mask dance is one of the sacred performing arts from Bali, Indonesia. Sidakarya has the meaning of achieving a goal or completing a job. The Sidakarya mask dance departs from a story about a Brahmin Keling who was not allowed to attend the Eka Dasa Rudra Ceremony at Besakih Temple after a long journey.
